phic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Basset","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: from a diminutive of Old French <i>bas(se)</i> ‘short, of low stature’ (see   Bas  ).","English: variant of   Bassett  , a cognate of 1 above.","In some cases also an altered form of French <b>Besset</b> (see   Bessette   2). Compare   Bassette   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Bas","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Mauricio, Abelardo, Florencio, Francisco, Jorge, Luis, Manuel, Pedro, Soledad, Vicente.  Eastern Slavic Dmytro, Liya, Pyotr, Sergey.","Catalan: habitational name from a place so named in the district of La Garrotxa, Catalonia.","Basque: topographic name for someone who lived by a wood, from <i>baso</i> ‘wood, forest’."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice de Basset was born about 1123, in Drayton, Penkridge, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Radulfus Sanford. They were the parents of at lea